docs: restructure README for 2026 - AI editors read, humans decide

Key insight from Chaos: the README is no longer read by a human end
to end. Humans only need enough info to decide whether the project
solves their problem. The detailed integration steps are read by AI
editors (Cursor / Claude Code / Kiro / Cline / Aider) on behalf of
the user.

Restructured README around this:

  Section 1-2: Why this exists + Three things that matter
  (human-facing - the sales pitch)

  Section 3: How to integrate - the prompt to hand to your AI editor
  (the primary CTA; humans copy one block of text, AI does the rest)

  Section 4+: Architecture, tiers, hospital metaphor, adapters
  (secondary - kept detailed because AI and curious humans both read
  them)

New file: LLMS.md - a complete, procedural integration guide written
for AI coding assistants. Covers framework detection, provider
selection, step-by-step file edits, common pitfalls, and what to
tell the user afterward.

Also updated the "What's next" section to announce the OpenClaw
plugin - the zero-code user experience for users who don't use an
AI editor.
